      { q: 'A student determines the resistivity of a wire by measuring its length, diameter and resistance. The measurements are: length = 0.750 ± 0.001 m, diameter = 0.28 ± 0.01 mm, resistance = 2.4 ± 0.1 Ω. Calculate the resistivity and its absolute uncertainty.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '• Area = π(d/2)² = π(0.28 × 10⁻³/2)² = 6.16 × 10⁻⁸ m² (1)\\n• ρ = RA/l = 2.4 × 6.16 × 10⁻⁸ / 0.750 = 1.97 × 10⁻⁷ Ω m (1)\\n• % uncertainty in l = (0.001/0.750) × 100 = 0.13% (1)\\n• % uncertainty in d = (0.01/0.28) × 100 = 3.57%, so % uncertainty in A = 2 × 3.57 = 7.14% (1)\\n• % uncertainty in R = (0.1/2.4) × 100 = 4.17% (1)\\n• Total % uncertainty = 0.13 + 7.14 + 4.17 = 11.4%, so absolute uncertainty = 0.114 × 1.97 × 10⁻⁷ = ± 0.2 × 10⁻⁷ Ω m (1)' },
      { q: 'Discuss the roles of random and systematic errors in an experiment to determine the acceleration due to gravity using a simple pendulum. Explain how each type can be identified and minimised.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '• Random errors cause scatter in repeated readings of period, e.g. due to reaction time or slight variations in release angle (1)\\n• They are identified by spread in data/error bars on a graph (1)\\n• Minimised by taking multiple readings and calculating a mean, or timing many oscillations (1)\\n• Systematic errors shift all values of g from the accepted value, e.g. measuring length to centre of bob rather than centre of mass, or parallax in length measurement (1)\\n• They are identified by comparing the experimental value with the accepted value (9.81 m s⁻²) (1)\\n• Minimised by careful experimental technique, calibration, and measuring from the correct reference point (1)' }
