      { q: 'Two objects, A (mass 3.0 kg, velocity 4.0 m s⁻¹ east) and B (mass 2.0 kg, velocity 5.0 m s⁻¹ north), collide and stick together. Calculate the speed and direction of the combined object after the collision.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '• Momentum is conserved in each direction separately (1)\\n• East: p_x = 3.0 × 4.0 = 12 kg m s⁻¹; North: p_y = 2.0 × 5.0 = 10 kg m s⁻¹ (1)\\n• Resultant momentum = √(12² + 10²) = √(244) = 15.6 kg m s⁻¹ (1)\\n• Speed = 15.6 / (3.0 + 2.0) = 3.12 m s⁻¹ at angle θ = tan⁻¹(10/12) = 39.8° north of east (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why a satellite in circular orbit has constant speed but is accelerating.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '• The satellite\'s velocity is constantly changing direction (it is a vector) (1)\\n• A change in velocity (even if only in direction) constitutes an acceleration (1)\\n• The gravitational force provides the centripetal acceleration directed towards the centre of the Earth, perpendicular to the velocity (1)' },
      { q: 'A ball on a string is whirled in a vertical circle of radius 0.80 m at constant speed. Explain why the tension in the string is greatest at the bottom of the circle.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '• At the bottom, the centripetal force is directed upwards (towards the centre) (1)\\n• The net upward force = T − mg = mv²/r (1)\\n• Therefore T = mv²/r + mg (tension must support weight AND provide centripetal force) (1)\\n• At the top, T + mg = mv²/r so T = mv²/r − mg, which is smaller than at the bottom (1)' }
