      { q: 'A snooker ball of mass 0.16 kg moving at 3.0 m s⁻¹ strikes a stationary ball of equal mass. After the collision, the first ball moves at 2.0 m s⁻¹ at 30° to its original direction. Calculate the speed and direction of the second ball, and determine whether kinetic energy is conserved.', marks: 7, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '• x-direction momentum: 0.16 × 3.0 = 0.16 × 2.0 cos30° + 0.16 × v₂cosθ (1)\\n• 3.0 = 1.732 + v₂cosθ, so v₂cosθ = 1.268 (1)\\n• y-direction momentum: 0 = 0.16 × 2.0 sin30° − 0.16 × v₂sinθ (1)\\n• v₂sinθ = 1.0 (1)\\n• v₂ = √(1.268² + 1.0²) = √(2.608) = 1.61 m s⁻¹ (1)\\n• θ = tan⁻¹(1.0/1.268) = 38.3° below original direction (1)\\n• KE before = ½(0.16)(3.0²) = 0.72 J; KE after = ½(0.16)(2.0²) + ½(0.16)(1.61²) = 0.32 + 0.208 = 0.528 J; KE is not conserved — inelastic (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain, using Newton\'s laws, why a car travelling over a hump-backed bridge of radius r experiences a reduction in the normal contact force at the top of the bridge. Derive an expression for the maximum speed at which the car can travel without losing contact with the road.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '• At the top of the bridge, the car follows a circular arc, so a centripetal force directed downwards (towards centre) is required (1)\\n• The forces acting are weight mg (down) and normal force N (up) (1)\\n• Applying Newton\'s second law towards centre: mg − N = mv²/r (1)\\n• Therefore N = mg − mv²/r; the normal force is reduced compared to its value on flat ground (mg) (1)\\n• The car loses contact when N = 0 (1)\\n• Setting N = 0: mg = mv²/r, so v_max = √(gr) (1)' }
