      { q: 'Describe the life cycle of a star with mass greater than about 8 solar masses, from protostar to its final remnant. Explain the physical processes at each stage.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '• Protostar forms from gravitational collapse of a gas/dust cloud (nebula); temperature rises as GPE converts to KE (1)\\n• Core temperature reaches ~10⁷ K and hydrogen fusion begins; the star joins the main sequence with radiation pressure balancing gravity (1)\\n• When hydrogen in the core is exhausted, the core contracts and heats; hydrogen shell burning causes outer layers to expand — becomes a red supergiant (1)\\n• Successive fusion reactions occur in shells: helium to carbon, then carbon, neon, oxygen, silicon up to iron (1)\\n• Iron fusion is endothermic so no further energy is released; the core collapses rapidly (in seconds) (1)\\n• Core collapse produces a neutron star (or black hole if mass is sufficient); a supernova explosion expels outer layers (1)\\n• Elements heavier than iron are formed during the supernova by neutron capture (1)\\n• Final remnant: neutron star (if core < ~3 solar masses) or black hole (if core > ~3 solar masses) (1)' },
      { q: 'Star A has surface temperature 5800 K and radius 7.0 × 10⁸ m. Star B has surface temperature 3500 K and radius 2.1 × 10¹⁰ m. Calculate the ratio of their luminosities and determine which star would appear brighter on an HR diagram. Identify likely classifications for each star.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '• L = 4πr²σT⁴ (1)\\n• L_A/L_B = (r_A/r_B)² × (T_A/T_B)⁴ = (7.0 × 10⁸ / 2.1 × 10¹⁰)² × (5800/3500)⁴ (1)\\n• (r_A/r_B)² = (1/30)² = 1/900 (1)\\n• (T_A/T_B)⁴ = (1.657)⁴ = 7.54 (1)\\n• L_A/L_B = 7.54/900 = 0.0084, so L_B ≈ 120 × L_A; Star B is much more luminous (1)\\n• Star A (T = 5800 K, moderate luminosity) is likely a main-sequence star similar to the Sun; Star B (T = 3500 K, very high luminosity, large radius) is a red giant/supergiant (1)' }
