      { q: 'State Kepler\'s third law and show how it can be derived from Newton\'s law of gravitation for a circular orbit.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '• Kepler\'s third law: T² is proportional to r³ (for orbits around the same central body) (1)\\n• For circular orbit: gravitational force provides centripetal force: GMm/r² = mv²/r (1)\\n• Since v = 2πr/T: GM/r² = (2πr/T)²/r = 4π²r/T² (1)\\n• Rearranging: T² = (4π²/GM)r³, confirming T² ∝ r³ (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between gravitational field strength and gravitational potential. State the mathematical relationship between them.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '• Gravitational field strength g is force per unit mass (a vector pointing towards the mass) (1)\\n• Gravitational potential V is work done per unit mass bringing a mass from infinity (a scalar, always negative) (1)\\n• g = −dV/dr (field strength is the negative gradient of potential) (1)' },
      { q: 'A satellite orbits Earth at a height of 400 km above the surface. Calculate its orbital speed. (Mass of Earth = 6.0 × 10²⁴ kg, radius of Earth = 6.4 × 10⁶ m, G = 6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ N m² kg⁻²)', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '• Orbital radius r = 6.4 × 10⁶ + 400 × 10³ = 6.8 × 10⁶ m (1)\\n• GMm/r² = mv²/r, so v = √(GM/r) = √(6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ × 6.0 × 10²⁴ / 6.8 × 10⁶) (1)\\n• v = √(5.88 × 10⁷) = 7670 m s⁻¹ ≈ 7.7 km s⁻¹ (1)' }
